result.execSummary:
The defendant Michael E Doege was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Misappropriate ID Info - Avoid Penalty, a class H felony, Wisconsin Statutes 943.201(2)(b).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant Michael E Doege in court with attorney Stephen M Compton.  Diane M. Donohoo appeared for the State of Wisconsin. Court in session @ 8:58 a.m. Appearances made. Matter before the Court on Defendant's Motion to withdraw his guilty plea. Parties are ready to proceed. 
8:59 a.m. - Atty Compton calls Michael Doege who is duly sworn and responds to direct exam.
9:03 a.m. - Cross exam by ADA Donohoo
9:22 a.m. - Redirect by Atty. Compton
9:23 a.m. - Witness excused. 
DE has no further witnesses/evidence. No evidence/witnesses for the State, but ADA Donohoo requests the Court take judicial notice of guilty plea questionnaire. Judge takes judicial notice of said document and transcript from the plea hearing.
Evidence closed.
9:25 a.m. - Argument by Attorney Compton
9:30 a.m. - Argument by ADA Donohoo
9:37 a.m. - Court makes a record as to record, standard, and has taken judicial notice of transcript, guilty plea questionnaire, motion and briefs. Court finds that plea questionnaire was adequate and appropriate. Court makes finding as to other reasons for defendant's motion, addressing contradictory statements made by the defendant during his testimony. Court goes through remaining points in defense motion and findings on each. Court finds that statements and other record are not fair or just reasons to withdraw his guilty plea. Court also finds that if granted, the State would be unduly prejudiced.  For all of reasons stated on the record, Court denies motion to withdraw guilty plea and sets matter for sentencing. Court in recess @ 9:56 a.m.  Sentencing hearing scheduled for October 21, 2016 at 03:30 pm.
